    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A school maps out four stations on a circular sports field boundary labeled <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m>. Ropes connect them sequentially to create quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m>. If the interior angle at station <m>A</m> is <m>\angle BAD = 78^\circ</m> and the interior angle at station <m>B</m> is <m>\angle ABC = 92^\circ</m>, calculate the measures of the remaining interior angles <m>\angle BCD</m> and <m>\angle ADC</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quadrilateral-stations">
    <caption>A circular sports field boundary with four stations forming cyclic quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m>, where <m>\angle BAD = 78^{\circ}</m> and <m>\angle ABC = 92^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle with four points A, B, C, and D on its circumference connected sequentially to form a quadrilateral. Opposite angles are marked with matching colors to illustrate the cyclic quadrilateral theorem.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle circumference ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Position the four points sequentially using reasonable angles to display the shape clearly
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 210 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 330 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{B}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 50 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{C}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 110 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{D}

            % Draw the main boundary circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, color=teal](O,B)

            % --- Draw the quadrilateral lines (ropes) ---
            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick, color=darkgray](A,B,C,D)

            % --- Fill and mark the interior angles ---
            % Pair 1: A and C (Opposite pairs)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!30,opacity=.7, size=.6](B,A,D)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!15,opacity=.7, size=.6](D,C,B)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](B,A,D)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](D,C,B)

            % Pair 2: B and D (Opposite pairs)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=magenta!20,opacity=.7, size=.6](C,B,A)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=magenta!10,opacity=.7, size=.6](A,D,C)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=magenta!80!black,thick](C,B,A)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=magenta!80!black,thick](A,D,C)

            % --- Angle value labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=.9](B,A,D){$78^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=.9](C,B,A){$92^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=.9](D,C,B){$?$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=.9](A,D,C){$?$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=5,fill=black](A,B,C,D)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below left,color=black](A)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below right,color=black](B)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above right,color=black](C)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above left,color=black](D)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Identify the opposite stations on the circular track: Station <m>A</m> faces station <m>C</m>, and station <m>B</m> faces station <m>D</m>.</p>
            <p>Apply the supplementary opposite angles property to find <m>\angle BCD</m>:
                <md>\angle BAD + \angle BCD = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>78^\circ + \angle BCD = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>\angle BCD = 180^\circ - 78^\circ = 102^\circ</md>
            </p>
            <p>Apply the property to find <m>\angle ADC</m>:
                <md>\angle ABC + \angle ADC = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>92^\circ + \angle ADC = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>\angle ADC = 180^\circ - 92^\circ = 88^\circ</md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A mechanic models four mounting bolt holes on a circular car wheel rim at positions <m>W</m>, <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, and <m>Z</m> to form a cyclic quadrilateral <m>WXYZ</m>. The straight rim edge segment <m>WX</m> is extended past vertex <m>X</m> to create an exterior alignment angle measuring <m>\angle YXE = 105^\circ</m>. Calculate the value of interior opposite angle <m>\angle WZY</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quad-exterior-thm">
    <caption>A circular car wheel rim modeling four mounting bolt holes that form cyclic quadrilateral <m>WXYZ</m>, where the straight edge segment <m>WX</m> is extended to <m>E</m> to form exterior angle <m>\angle YXE = 105^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A geometry diagram of a cyclic quadrilateral WXYZ inside a circle. The bottom edge line segment WX extends outwards to a point E on the right, forming an exterior angle at vertex X labeled 105 degrees, with the opposite interior angle at vertex Z marked with a question mark.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle circumference ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Define positions around the circle perimeter
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 200 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{W}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 320 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{X}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 45 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Y}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 105 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Z}

            % Project an external point E past X to show the line continuation straight out
            \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center W ratio 1.4](X)\tkzGetPoint{E}

            % Draw outer boundary wheel rim circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, color=teal](O,Y)

            % --- Draw the inner structural edges ---
            \tkzDrawSegments[thick, color=darkgray](X,Y Y,Z Z,W)
            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, color=purple](W,E) % Extended base edge segment

            % --- Fill and color angle arcs ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=magenta!25,opacity=.7, size=.6](E,X,Y)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!20,opacity=.7, size=.6](W,Z,Y)
            
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=magenta!80!black,thick](E,X,Y)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](W,Z,Y)

            % --- Math text annotations ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](E,X,Y){$105^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.9](W,Z,Y){$?$}

            % --- Dot indicators and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=5,fill=black](W,X,Y,Z)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below left,color=black](W)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below,color=black](X)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above right,color=black](Y)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above left,color=black](Z)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right,color=purple](E)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Apply the exterior angle property of a cyclic quadrilateral: The exterior angle formed by extending a side is equal to the interior opposite angle across the circle.</p>
            <p>Identify the correct opposite relationship: For the exterior angle at vertex <m>X</m>, the interior opposite angle is located at vertex <m>Z</m> (<m>\angle WZY</m>).</p>
            <p>State the conclusion directly:
                <md>\angle WZY = \angle YXE = 105^\circ</md>
                The interior structural angle at vertex <m>Z</m> is <m>105^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A designer plans four placeholder settings on a round dining table surface labeled <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, and <m>S</m> sequentially. The opposite interior angles are expressed as algebraic values where <m>\angle QPS = 3x + 20^\circ</m> and <m>\angle QRS = 2x + 10^\circ</m>. Determine the value of <m>x</m> and the true measure of <m>\angle QPS</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quad-placeholder-settings">
    <caption>A round dining table surface with four placeholder settings forming a cyclic quadrilateral <m>PQRS</m>, where opposite interior angles are <m>\angle QPS = 3x + 20^{\circ}</m> and <m>\angle QRS = 2x + 10^{\circ}</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle layout showing a cyclic quadrilateral PQRS inside. Opposite vertices P and R are highlighted with shaded angle areas to visually demonstrate that their sum equals 180 degrees.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle circumference ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Position the four points sequentially to show a clear quadrilateral geometry
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 140 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{P}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 230 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{Q}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 330 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{R}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 50 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{S}

            % Draw the table boundary circle
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, color=teal](O,R)

            % --- Draw the quadrilateral table pattern lines ---
            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick, color=darkgray](P,Q,R,S)

            % --- Fill and mark the opposite interior angle pairs ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!30,opacity=.7, size=.6](Q,P,S)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!15,opacity=.7, size=.6](S,R,Q)
            
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](Q,P,S)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](S,R,Q)

            % --- Geometric mathematical text annotations ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.1](Q,P,S){$3x + 20^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.1](S,R,Q){$2x + 10^{\circ}$}

            % --- Points and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=5,fill=black](P,Q,R,S)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above left,color=black](P)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below left,color=black](Q)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below right,color=black](R)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above right,color=black](S)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Since the settings lie on the circle's edge, <m>PQRS</m> forms a cyclic quadrilateral, meaning opposite interior angles must sum to <m>180^\circ</m>:
                <md>\angle QPS + \angle QRS = 180^\circ</md>
            </p>
            <p>Substitute the algebraic expressions:
                <md>(3x + 20^\circ) + (2x + 10^\circ) = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>5x + 30^\circ = 180^\circ</md>
            </p>
            <p>Isolate and solve for <m>x</m>:
                <md>5x = 180^\circ - 30^\circ</md>
                <md>5x = 150^\circ</md>
                <md>x = 30^\circ</md>
            </p>
            <p>Calculate the measure of <m>\angle QPS</m>:
                <md>\angle QPS = 3(30^\circ) + 20^\circ = 90^\circ + 20^\circ = 110^\circ</md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A circular dome greenhouse frame connects four joints <m>K</m>, <m>L</m>, <m>M</m>, and <m>N</m>. An outer horizontal pathway extends straight past joint <m>N</m> along the line segment <m>MN</m> to an exterior support post <m>G</m>. If the interior opposite angle across the frame is <m>\angle KLM = 85^\circ</m>, determine the size of the exterior joint angle <m>\angle KNG</m>.</p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quad-greenhouse">
    <caption>A circular dome greenhouse frame connecting four joints <m>K, L, M, N</m> where the pathway segment <m>MN</m> is extended past joint <m>N</m> to an exterior support post <m>G</m> to create an exterior joint angle <m>\angle KNG</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle layout showing an inscribed cyclic quadrilateral KLMN representing a greenhouse frame. The line segment MN is extended horizontally past vertex N to an exterior point G, demonstrating that the exterior angle KNG equals the interior opposite angle KLM of 85 degrees.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle boundary ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Position the four cyclic quadrilateral joint points sequentially
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 125 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{K}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 220 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{L}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 330 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{M}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 45 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{N}

            % Project an exterior support point G straight along the extended path of MN
            \tkzDefPointBy[homothety=center M ratio 1.45](N)\tkzGetPoint{G}

            % Draw the greenhouse outer circular boundary rim
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, color=teal](O,N)

            % --- Draw structural framing and the extended pathway path ---
            \tkzDrawSegments[thick, color=darkgray](K,L L,M K,N)
            \tkzDrawSegment[thick, color=purple](M,G) % Extended structural path MN straight to G

            % --- Highlight and mark the corresponding theorem angles ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!30,opacity=.7, size=.6](M,L,K)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!15,opacity=.7, size=.6](G,N,K)
            
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](M,L,K)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](G,N,K)

            % --- Mathematical text labels ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.9](M,L,K){$85^{\circ}$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.9](G,N,K){$?$}

            % --- Frame node indicators and labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=5,fill=black](K,L,M,N)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above left,color=black](K)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below left,color=black](L)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below right,color=black](M)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above right,color=black](N)
            \tkzLabelPoints[right,color=purple](G)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Recognize the geometric framework: The joints form an inscribed cyclic quadrilateral <m>KLMN</m>, and extending side <m>MN</m> creates the exterior angle <m>\angle KNG</m> at vertex <m>N</m>.</p>
            <p>Apply the exterior angle theorem: The exterior angle is identical in measure to the interior opposite angle directly across the shape.
                <md>\angle KNG = \angle KLM</md>
                <md>\angle KNG = 85^\circ</md>
                The exterior joint angle measures <m>85^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Four landmark statues are positioned on the perimeter of a circular town square plaza at positions <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m>. Pedestrian pathways connect them to form quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m>. The blueprint notes that <m>\angle ABC</m> is exactly twice the size of its opposite interior angle <m>\angle ADC</m>. Calculate both angle measures.</p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quad-landmark-statues">
    <caption>A circular town square plaza with four landmark statues positioned at <m>A, B, C, D</m> connected by pathways, where the interior angle <m>\angle ABC</m> is exactly twice the size of its opposite angle <m>\angle ADC</m>.</caption>
    <image width="65%">
        <description>A circle layout showing an inscribed cyclic quadrilateral ABCD modeling a plaza pathway network. Opposite angles B and D are filled with contrasting colors to highlight that one is double the size of the other, summing to 180 degrees.</description>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            % --- Centre and points on the circle circumference ---
            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}

            % Position the four points sequentially around the town square plaza
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 200 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{A}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 310 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{B}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 40 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{C}
            \tkzDefPointOnCircle[R = center O angle 100 radius 3]\tkzGetPoint{D}

            % Draw the circular plaza boundary fence
            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, color=teal](O,B)

            % --- Draw the pedestrian pathway polygon lines ---
            \tkzDrawPolygon[thick, color=darkgray](A,B,C,D)

            % --- Fill and mark the opposite interior angle pairs ---
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=magenta!20,opacity=.7, size=.6](C,B,A)
            \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!20,opacity=.7, size=.6](A,D,C)
            
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=magenta!80!black,thick](C,B,A)
            \tkzMarkAngle[size=.6,color=cyan!80!black,thick](A,D,C)

            % --- Geometric mathematical text annotations ---
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.0](C,B,A){$2x$}
            \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.9](A,D,C){$x$}

            % --- Landmark nodes and point labels ---
            \tkzDrawPoints[size=5,fill=black](A,B,C,D)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below left,color=black](A)
            \tkzLabelPoints[below right,color=black](B)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above right,color=black](C)
            \tkzLabelPoints[above left,color=black](D)

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
</figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Define the relationship using a variable: Let the smaller opposite angle <m>\angle ADC = x</m>. This means <m>\angle ABC = 2x</m>.</p>
            <p>Since opposite angles in a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary:
                <md>\angle ABC + \angle ADC = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>2x + x = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>3x = 180^\circ</md>
                <md>x = 60^\circ</md>
            </p>
            <p>State the measure of each plaza walkway angle:
                <md>\angle ADC = 60^\circ</md>
                <md>\angle ABC = 2(60^\circ) = 120^\circ</md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

